{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17998"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17998"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.48,0.05,0.14,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10712"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64181"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27036"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the vertebral column is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The vertebral foramen transmits the spinal nerves.","The vertebral arch is composed of pedicles, laminae, and processes.","The innermost part of the vertebral body is made up of cortical bone.","The vertebral arch is directly involved in weight bearing.","The outermost part of the vertebral body is made up of spongy bone."],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe vertebral arch is composed of pedicles, laminae, and processes\u003C/strong\u003E, which together form the posterior part of the vertebra and protect the spinal cord. This is the correct statement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe vertebral arch is not directly involved in weight bearing\u003C/strong\u003E; instead, it provides protection for the spinal cord and serves as an attachment point for muscles and ligaments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe outermost part of the vertebral body\u003C/strong\u003E is actually made up of cortical bone, which provides strength and support, while the inner part is composed of spongy bone, which helps absorb shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe vertebral foramen\u003C/strong\u003E transmits the spinal cord, not the spinal nerves. The spinal nerves exit the vertebral column through the intervertebral foramina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe innermost part of the vertebral body\u003C/strong\u003E is made up of spongy bone, not cortical bone. The spongy bone is surrounded by a thin layer of cortical bone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vertebral arch is not directly involved in weight bearing; it primarily protects the spinal cord.","The vertebral body is primarily composed of spongy bone internally, surrounded by a thin layer of cortical bone.","The vertebral arch is composed of pedicles, laminae, and processes.","The vertebral foramen transmits the spinal cord, not the spinal nerves."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17998"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64181"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T20:45:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T20:45:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10712"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78832"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t